//?Telnet (older way of connection) (port :23):
It is the older way of connectig one server(shell) to other server(shell) and we can we use now as well.
But is not a secure connection between servers in between the connection there is a chance of getting the credentials to
be hacked in between the connection and there is chance that what commands we execute also be know by them.



SSH : secure shell (port :22)
In this connection the first machine encrypts the userid and password and then send to other machine and it will decrypts and 
checks the user name and password and it will helps the user to login to the server.

It uses rsa alogarithm to login to the server to encrypt the userid and password.

It uses a tunneling technique.

server----tunneling----server

we are encrypting the id's from one server and in other server  will be decrypt that user id and password.


configuration file for sshd : cat /etc/ssh/sshd_config :--
------------------------------------------------------

-->open it with vi editor vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config

--->search with permit  : like /permit enter

--->it shows -->password authentication is yes (then it will connect from one server to other server with password )

Password less login :
---------------------
Generating ssh key pair : For generating ssh key we need to use command ---->ssh-keygen 
 1)it will generate in (-->cd /root/.ssh)  .
 2)After generating we have two keys i.e, (id_rsa -- private key , id_rsa.pub -- public key)
 3)copy the public key and paste it in the server which you want to login (Ex ssh-copy-id  -i /root/.ssh/id_rsa.pub 192.168.138.135)
 4)close the sessions in putty and try again .
 5)it will not ask for password.
 
 *** sshd -t ----------> it will show if we have any login errors in the servers.

