SCP(secure copy) :
-----------------
1)It is used to copy the data from one server to other server.

Syntax-->scp [options] [source] [destination]

-r: Recursively copy entire directories.
-P port: Specify the port to connect to on the remote host (note the uppercase P).
-p: Preserves the modification times, access times, and modes of the original file.
-q: Suppress the progress meter.
-v: Enable verbose mode for debugging.

*Copy a local file to a remote host:

scp /path/to/local/file user@remote_host:/path/to/remote/directory

**Copy a file from a remote host to a local machine:

scp user@remote_host:/path/to/remote/file /path/to/local/directory

***Copy an entire directory to a remote host:

scp -r /path/to/local/directory user@remote_host:/path/to/remote/directory

****Copy a file to a specific port on a remote host:

scp -P 2222 /path/to/local/file user@remote_host:/path/to/remote/directory

*****Copy from one remote host to another:

scp user1@remote_host1:/path/to/file user2@remote_host2:/path/to/destination


   Ensure you have SSH access to the remote host.
   You may be prompted to enter a password for the remote user unless youâ€™ve set up SSH keys for passwordless login.
 
RSYNC(remote syncronised ) command:
---------------------------------
1)It is for backing up of files or directories from one machine other for keeping to machines in sync.
2)In case of scp if the connection losts from one system other then we need to start everything from scratch.
In case of rsync it will not it will start form whereever it has ended.It is design to speed up the copy of two machines.
3)if we use the scp command it will take everything to copy but the rsync command will do whatever we have modified that will
only be synced that when we copied.

-------command :--rsync -rv -e ssh /batch7AM  192.168.195.135:/

here r--recursive
     v--verbose
	 e--ssh 

4)And do some modifications and again and run same command it willl sync only data not files again.


